css.css selectors:
CSS selectors target HTML elements to apply styles. Common selectors include element selectors (p), class selectors (.classname), ID selectors (#idname), attribute selectors ([type='text']), and combinators (descendant, child, sibling).<div class='responsediv'><pre>p { color: blue; }
.classname { font-size: 16px; }
#idname { background-color: yellow; }</pre></div>

css.css color:
Colors in CSS can be specified using color names, hexadecimal values, RGB, HSL, or RGBA for transparency.<div class='responsediv'><pre>color: red;
color: #FF0000;
color: rgb(255, 0, 0);
color: rgba(255, 0, 0, 0.5);</pre></div>

css.css fonts:
The `font-family` property specifies typefaces. CSS supports web-safe fonts and custom fonts via `@font-face`. Common font properties include `font-size`, `font-weight`, `font-style`, and `line-height`.<div class='responsediv'><pre>font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
font-size: 16px;
font-weight: bold;
font-style: italic;</pre></div>

css.css box model:
The CSS Box Model consists of content, padding, border, and margin. Padding is inside the border, margin is outside. The `box-sizing` property controls whether width/height includes padding and border.<div class='responsediv'><pre>padding: 10px;
border: 1px solid black;
margin: 20px;
box-sizing: border-box;</pre></div>

css.css margin:
Margin creates space outside an element's border. Use margin to space elements apart. Margins can collapse vertically between block elements.<div class='responsediv'><pre>margin: 20px;
margin-top: 10px;
margin: 10px 20px 10px 20px;</pre></div>

css.css padding:
Padding creates space inside an element, between content and the border. Unlike margin, padding does not collapse.<div class='responsediv'><pre>padding: 15px;
padding-left: 20px;
padding: 10px 15px;</pre></div>

css.css border:
Borders surround elements and can be styled with width, style, and color. Common styles include solid, dashed, dotted, and double.<div class='responsediv'><pre>border: 2px solid black;
border-radius: 5px;
border-top: 1px dashed red;</pre></div>

css.css display:
The `display` property controls how elements are rendered. Common values are `block`, `inline`, `inline-block`, `flex`, `grid`, and `none`.<div class='responsediv'><pre>display: block;
display: inline;
display: flex;
display: grid;</pre></div>

css.css positioning:
CSS positioning controls element placement. Position types are `static` (default), `relative`, `absolute`, `fixed`, and `sticky`. Use `top`, `right`, `bottom`, `left`, and `z-index` to position elements.<div class='responsediv'><pre>position: relative;
top: 20px;
position: absolute;
z-index: 10;</pre></div>

css.css flex properties:
Flex container properties: `flex-direction` (row/column), `justify-content` (main axis alignment), `align-items` (cross axis alignment), `flex-wrap`, `gap`. Flex item properties: `flex`, `flex-grow`, `flex-shrink`, `flex-basis`, `align-self`.<div class='responsediv'><pre>display: flex;
justify-content: center;
align-items: center;
flex-direction: row;</pre></div>

css.css grid:
CSS Grid is a two-dimensional layout system for creating complex layouts. Use `display: grid`, `grid-template-columns`, `grid-template-rows`, `gap`, and `grid-area` to define grids.<div class='responsediv'><pre>display: grid;
grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr 1fr;
grid-gap: 20px;
grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto;</pre></div>

css.css grid properties:
Grid container properties: `grid-template-columns`, `grid-template-rows`, `gap`, `justify-items`, `align-items`. Grid item properties: `grid-column`, `grid-row`, `justify-self`, `align-self`.<div class='responsediv'><pre>grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
grid-column: 1 / 3;
grid-row: 2;</pre></div>

css.css background:
The `background` property controls element backgrounds. Use `background-color`, `background-image`, `background-size`, `background-position`, and `background-repeat`.<div class='responsediv'><pre>background-color: #f0f0f0;
background-image: url('image.jpg');
background-size: cover;
background-position: center;</pre></div>

css.css text:
Text properties include `color`, `text-align`, `text-decoration`, `text-transform`, `text-shadow`, `letter-spacing`, and `word-spacing`.<div class='responsediv'><pre>text-align: center;
text-decoration: underline;
text-transform: uppercase;
text-shadow: 2px 2px 4px rgba(0,0,0,0.3);</pre></div>

css.css animations:
Animations create complex motion sequences using `@keyframes`. Define animation using `animation`, `animation-duration`, `animation-timing-function`, and `animation-iteration-count`.<div class='responsediv'><pre>@keyframes slide {
  from { left: 0; }
  to { left: 100px; }
}
animation: slide 1s ease-in-out;</pre></div>

css.css transforms:
CSS transforms modify element appearance: `translate()`, `rotate()`, `scale()`, `skew()`, and combinations with `transform-origin`.<div class='responsediv'><pre>transform: translate(20px, 10px);
transform: rotate(45deg);
transform: scale(1.5);</pre></div>

css.css overflow:
The `overflow` property controls content that exceeds container dimensions: `visible`, `hidden`, `scroll`, `auto`.<div class='responsediv'><pre>overflow: hidden;
overflow-x: scroll;
overflow-y: auto;</pre></div>

css.css pseudo-classes:
Pseudo-classes target elements in specific states: `:hover`, `:focus`, `:active`, `:visited`, `:first-child`, `:last-child`, `:nth-child()`, `:not()`.<div class='responsediv'><pre>a:hover { color: red; }
input:focus { border-color: blue; }
li:nth-child(2) { background: yellow; }</pre></div>

css.css media queries:
Media queries apply styles based on device characteristics like screen width. Use `@media` with conditions like `max-width`, `min-width`, `orientation`.<div class='responsediv'><pre>@media (max-width: 768px) {
  body { font-size: 14px; }
}</pre></div>

css.css filter:
CSS filters apply visual effects: `blur()`, `brightness()`, `contrast()`, `grayscale()`, `saturate()`, `sepia()`, `drop-shadow()`.<div class='responsediv'><pre>filter: blur(5px);
filter: brightness(1.2);
filter: grayscale(100%);</pre></div>

javascript.js objects:
Objects store key-value pairs. Access properties via dot notation or bracket notation. Methods are functions stored as properties.<div class='responsediv'><pre>const person = { name: 'Alice', age: 25 };
person.age = 26;
const name = person['name'];</pre></div>

javascript.js template literals:
Template literals use backticks and `${}` for variable interpolation, supporting multi-line strings.<div class='responsediv'><pre>const name = 'Alice';
const greeting = `Hello, ${name}!
Welcome!`;</pre></div>

javascript.js spread operator:
The spread operator (`...`) expands arrays or objects into individual elements or properties.<div class='responsediv'><pre>const arr1 = [1, 2];
const arr2 = [...arr1, 3, 4];
const obj2 = { ...obj1, newProp: 'value' };</pre></div>

javascript.js if else:
Conditional statements execute code based on conditions using `if`, `else if`, and `else`.<div class='responsediv'><pre>if (x > 0) {
    console.log('Positive');
} else if (x === 0) {
    console.log('Zero');
} else {
    console.log('Negative');
}</pre></div>

javascript.js switch:
The `switch` statement evaluates an expression and executes code based on matching cases.<div class='responsediv'><pre>switch (day) {
    case 1: console.log('Monday'); break;
    case 2: console.log('Tuesday'); break;
    default: console.log('Other');
}</pre></div>

javascript.js promises:
Promises represent eventual completion or failure of asynchronous operations. States: `pending`, `fulfilled`, `rejected`.<div class='responsediv'><pre>const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    if (success) resolve(value);
    else reject(error);
});</pre></div>

javascript.js async await:
`async` functions return promises. `await` pauses execution until a promise resolves, enabling cleaner asynchronous code.<div class='responsediv'><pre>async function fetchData() {
    const data = await fetch(url);
    return data.json();
}</pre></div>

javascript.js class:
Classes are syntactic sugar for prototype-based inheritance, providing cleaner object creation.<div class='responsediv'><pre>class Animal {
    constructor(name) { this.name = name; }
    sound() { console.log('Sound'); }
}</pre></div>

javascript.js iife:
Immediately Invoked Function Expressions (IIFE) execute immediately upon definition, creating a new scope.<div class='responsediv'><pre>(function() {
    const privateVar = 'secret';
})();</pre></div>

